<TEXT>
a sixman crew determined to break the record 
for a transatlantic voyage set off sunday from new york aboard a 
6 million speedboat 
honolulu businessman thomas gentry 57 and his crew passed 
ambrose light just outside new york harbor at 1126 am sunday to 
start the race across the north atlantic to bishop rock off great 
britains isles of scilly race spokesman mark jaffe said 
the 110foot 11460 horsepower gentrycontinental proud bird 
sponsored by continental airlines will attempt to cross the 
atlantic in less than 72 hours the current record time of 3 days 
8 hours and 31 minutes was set in 1986 by englishman richard 
branson 
branson who owns virgin atlantic airways and several other 
companies set his record on june 29 1986 in the virgin atlantic 
challenger ii it was bransons second attempt at the crossing his 
first attempt in may 1985 failed when the original virgin 
atlantic challenger sank 138 miles short of the finish 
crew member jeffery brown speaking by radiotelephone said the 
proud bird had passed over the nantucket shoals about 330 pm 
sunday the vessel was cruising at 50 knots through sixfoot swells 
and fog he said 
wed like a little smoother seas brown said 
basically the autopilot is doing the driving and were just 
kind of cruising along he said 
however the boats size speed and sea conditions were making 
for a rough passage 
its not a comfy ride theres a rolling and pitching motion 
and when you hit these swells you feel a few inches shorter and 
like youve been punched in the stomach brown reported 
