moslem separatists burned seven rural 
schools in the southern province of narathiwat in an apparent 
attempt to disrupt thailands general elections on sunday a 
district official said 
the official who asked not to be identified said the rebels 
torched the schools and a health clinic in isolated areas of three 
districts in the province after midnight saturday 
polling booths had been set up in some of the schools and the 
official linked the raids to efforts by moslems to disrupt the 
voting that began at 8 am 9 pm edt 
a total of 3606 candidates from 16 parties are vying for 357 
seats in the house of representatives since no party is expected 
to gain a majority several parties will probably team up to choose 
a prime minister who then forms a government 
prime minister prem tinsulanonda who does not belong to any 
party is widely predicted to return to his post heading a 
coalition of several parties he has held office since 1980 
the district official contacted by telephone said four of the 
schools burned to the ground while three others and the clinic were 
damaged but he said polling at the schools was able to proceed 
despite the nighttime raid 
moslems who form a minority in thailand are the majority in 
the province bordering malaysia the country as a whole is 
predominantly buddhist 
several hundred moslem separatists believed to be supported by 
radical groups in the middle east operate in the thaimalaysian 
border area the separatists have called for a merger with malaysia 
or various forms of autonomy 
prem called the election 24 months early after he dissolved 
parliament april 29 disbanding his factionridden coalition 
government 
the 67yearold former army commander voted in the provincial 
capital of korat northeast of bangkok but he has not said whether 
he would accept another term 
thai elections are largely centered on personalities not 
political platforms and the main contention has been whether prem 
should return or not 
although his popularity has been waning most leaders of the 
four current coalition parties back his return and he remains 
favored by three institutions which figure in the choice of a prime 
minister the military bureaucracy and constitutional monarchy 
whoever emerges as the new prime minister is almost certainly to 
keep thailand on the same general course of economically 
conservative politically prowestern policies the economy has 
boomed in the past two years 
the present coalition government comprises the democrat party of 
deputy prime minister bhichai rattakul the chart thai thai 
nation of deputy prime minister chatichai choonhavan the social 
action party of foreign minister siddhi savetsila and the 
rassadorn citizens party of deputy prime minister thienchai 
sirisamphan 
