<TEXT>
polaroid corp which first gave the 
world instant snapshots more than half a century ago has been 
thrust into the public eye in 1988 by a series of highstakes 
events that portend significant changes for the company 
on wall street analysts and arbitragers are fascinated by the 
possibility of an allout takeover battle for polaroid prompted by 
a hostile bid last week from a californiabased investment group 
led by an heir to the disney entertainment empire 
in the courts the outcome of a 57 billion patent infringement 
suit against rival eastman kodak co could have a major impact on 
polaroid stock prices 
and in its headquarters along the charles river company 
officials are trimming the work force while preparing to challenge 
kodak and other film manufacturers with the worldwide introduction 
of conventional color film 
polaroid with a reputation for extravagant research and 
uninspired marketing now faces quick and important decisions 
were all waiting to see what happens said eugene glazer 
an analyst at dean witter reynolds inc in new york polaroid is 
hot right now 
polaroids tumultuous year began dramatically in late february 
with its 57 billion damage claim in the us district court 
patent suit 
polaroid claims it lost 32 billion in sales and 25 billion 
in business opportunities after kodak entered the instant camera 
field in 1976 
us district court judge rya zobel ruled in 1985 that kodak 
violated seven polaroid patents and ordered the rochester 
nybased company to halt production of the instant film and 
camera zobel last month withdrew from the 12yearold case due to 
family holdings of kodak stock the damages portion of the case is 
scheduled to be heard in january with a new judge presiding 
although kodak termed the damage claim ludicrous and 
ridiculously inflated polaroid stock has risen sharply from the 
mid20 range in anticipation of a decision in polaroids favor 
polaroid closed at 4075 a share friday on the new york stock 
exchange largely because of takeover talk 
the company would welcome any award even the 1 billion to 2 
billion many analysts predict following several years of 
lackluster performance polaroid camera sales have dropped nearly 
50 percent from a high of 75 million in 1978 and the public has 
poorly received several new products such as video film 
polaroid was formed in 1937 by dr edwin land jr to develop and 
manufacture a synthetic light polarizing material he developed 
polaroid produced instant color photography in 1963 and made its 
most stunning achievement in 1972 with the release of the sx70 
system which produced instant pictures outside the camera 
it has made ventures in other market areas but with nowhere near 
the success of its breakthroughs in instant photography 
amid takeover rumors the company on july 12 announced a 
reorganization plan highlighted by 500 to 800 layoffs and its entry 
into the 7 billionayear conventional film market 
company officials would not announce when the new film will be 
available outside spain and portugal where it has been sold for 
two years in direct competition with industry leaders kodak 
agfagevaert and fuji photo film co ltd 
meanwhile the layoffs mark the latest in a decadelong 
reduction in polaroids work force which has declined from more 
than 20000 in 1978 to nearly 13000 a company statement said most 
employees could select either early retirement or a severance plan 
that provided up to one years salary 
in addition the company issued 10 million new shares into an 
employee stock ownership plan and launched a 300 million company 
stock repurchase effort the move was interpreted as an effort to 
discourage takeover attempts 
but less than a week later shamrock holdings inc a television 
and radio concern based in burbank calif made a 40pershare 
bid for polaroid and filed suit in delaware seeking to cancel the 
employee stock purchase plan 
shamrock owned by the family of roy e disney a walt disney 
co director and nephew of the famous animator disclosed on july 
20 it had acquired 493 million polaroid shares as of may 11 
its takeover bid values the company at about 288 billion if 
all 719 million shares remain outstanding however shamrock has 
indicated it might not proceed unless it manages to get the recent 
10 millionshare issue rolled back in that case the implied value 
of the bid would be 248 billion 
because shamrock already owns a large block its cost to buy the 
rest would be 228 billion assuming defeat of the share issue or 
268 billion if the share issue is not defeated 
according to shamrock documents polaroid president and chief 
executive officer i macallister booth refused to meet with disney 
earlier this year to discuss company strategies booth eventually 
consented to a july 13 meeting on condition that shamrock would not 
acquire additional polaroid stock and polaroid in turn take no 
action which might hurt shamrocks investment 
the meeting was not held in the wake of polaroids 
reorganization announcement which shamrock termed a clear 
breach of its agreement with polaroid the company said it would 
convene directors tuesday to discuss the shamrock bid 
some analysts are skeptical the 10yearold shamrock group could 
put together a deal of such magnitude 
earlier this year shamrock failed in a 92 million bid for 
wherehouse entertainment a california video rental and music 
company shamrock owns music plus a 54store music and video 
retail chain in the los angeles area in addition to three 
television stations and 14 radio stations 
as far as im concerned its a very shaky bid said glazer 
there seems to be too many conditions attatched to the offer 
it just seems out of their league 
william relyea an analyst at dean witter reynolds inc in new 
york said shamrock could have a major impact on investors if it 
could arrange a tender offer at a lower price with a promise to 
distribute any dividends to shareholders following resolution of 
the kodak suit 
say for example they got polaroid for 30 a share said 
relyea well that would set the damage award at about 10 a 
share when right now no one can really say what effect it will 
have 
the offer by shamrock also could lure other suitors hostile or 
friendly into the bidding for polaroid analysts say 
</TEXT>
