<TEXT>
the hunt brothers texas oil operation has offered 
to pay 8035 million to settle the final step in a bitter twoyear 
court battle between hunt companies and banks that lent them 15 
billion according to company officials 
the offer by placid oil co which is owned by hunt trust 
estates includes cash repayments of 6635 million over the next 
two months the hunts also would to pay the banks 140 million from 
placid production revenues during the next seven years company 
officials said saturday 
the plan which is subject to approval by federal bankruptcy 
court internal revenue service and major creditor groups nearly 
would complete the settlement of the case and would remove placid 
from bankruptcy protection 
it also would leave the billionaire hunt brothers with only 
pieces of the vast petroleumbased empire amassed by their father 
dallas wildcatter hl hunt 
late in june the hunt trusts and bank creditors agreed on a 
settlement to resolve issues surrounding some 760 million in loans 
to their penrod drilling co 
penrod the worlds biggest independent offshore oildrilling 
company and placid oil sued 23 of their lenders for fraud and 
misrepresentation in 1986 after defaulting on 15 billion in bank 
loans two of the banks since have been dropped from the case 
the suit sought 14 million in damages alleging the banks 
conspired to drive penrod and placid out of business by forcing 
them to agree to an unreasonable payment schedule while offering 
their competitors more favorable terms 
in august 1986 the trust estates of william herbert hunt 
nelson bunker hunt and lamar hunt filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy 
protection for the trust partnership that owns penrod drilling 
the reorganization plan proposed for placid calls for sale of 
the hunt brothers interests in the 60story thanksgiving tower a 
downtown dallas office building and disposal of hunt production 
properties in louisiana transactions that are completed or pending 
it depends on a number of large transactions hunt attorney 
henry simon said of the proposal 
simon said one obstacle to conclusion of the settlement was the 
negotiation under way in the netherlands for a loan of about 245 
million to be secured by placid international oil the hunts 
north sea unit 
the hunts already have paid 2135 million of the proposed 
6635 million cash settlement from funds raised through placid 
operations primarily the north sea unit as part of cash 
collateral agreements with bank lenders said simon 
another 150 million was raised through sale of the hunts black 
lake oil and gas fields in louisiana he said 
the brothers also plan to apply to the settlement their share of 
the 50 million in proceeds expected from pending sale of an 80 
percent interest in thanksgiving tower the planned sale of the 
building to bear stearns amp co a new york investment banking 
firm should be complete by midaugust said simon 
he said completion of the loan agreement associated with the 
north sea assets could come by early september but was dependent on 
negotiations under way with mortgage lenders who must approve the 
transaction 
the plan would leave the hunts with placids successful north 
sea operations and prospects in the green canyon sector of the gulf 
of mexico 
under the proposal to resolve the penrod loans bank creditors 
would receive a 50 million payment and a 500 million secured note 
from penrod drilling plus a 50 percent interest in the company if 
the hunts fail to meet certain debt repayment deadlines 
some trust real estate will be transferred to the banks subject 
to a 200 million purchase option 
the penrod plan also must be approved by federal bankruptcy 
court 
</TEXT>
